1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:05,720
90% of small account traders fail, 
because they chase massive gains! 

2
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:10,200
They end up blowing their accounts, 
trying to double their money fast. 

3
00:00:10,200 --> 00:00:17,174
Let me show you the fastest, and the safest 
way, to grow a small account when day trading!
  

4
00:00:17,174 --> 00:00:19,520
The 1% Daily Goal Strategy
Aim to make 1% of your account  

5
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:26,640
each day through 2 or 3 well-planned trades.
This should add up to at least 10% monthly  

6
00:00:26,640 --> 00:00:31,240
when compounded, making it 
realistic for small accounts. 

7
00:00:31,240 --> 00:00:38,160
I said 10% and no 20% because let’s face 
it, you won’t end every day on profit. 

8
00:00:38,160 --> 00:00:43,880
But a 10% gain on a month is 
doable, if you follow these rules.
  

9
00:00:43,880 --> 00:00:49,480
You see, many traders fail because they 
chase big wins right from the start. 

10
00:00:49,480 --> 00:00:55,320
They see a Youtuber flashing his “rented” 
car, they believe he turned 100 dollars into  

11
00:00:55,320 --> 00:01:00,320
half a million in a few months, so 
they enter into “gambling” state. 

12
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:04,320
You’re better than that!
Instead of aiming for huge gains,  

13
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:10,640
split your daily target into 2-3 trades.
Each trade only needs to bring in a  

14
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:14,840
small profit to reach your goal.
This simple approach will keep  

15
00:01:14,840 --> 00:01:19,040
your emotions in check, and prevents 
the common mistake of overtrading.
  

16
00:01:19,040 --> 00:01:26,960
You need a solid foundation first.
I know a steady 1% daily gain might sound small,  

17
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:32,440
and I repeat, you won’t hit it every day.
But money grows faster than you think,  

18
00:01:32,440 --> 00:01:38,680
when you let compounding work its magic.
Your small account CAN expand without taking  

19
00:01:38,680 --> 00:01:43,720
crazy risks that blow up your account.
 
The best part is that you don't  

20
00:01:43,720 --> 00:01:49,520
need to catch every big market move.
While others chase the next hot stock,  

21
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:56,720
you can focus on finding small, repeatable 
patterns that consistently deliver modest profits. 

22
00:01:56,720 --> 00:02:01,000
Use small contract sizes if needed 
- there's no shame in starting  

23
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,040
super small, while you prove your system works.
Your account size shouldn't change how you trade. 

24
00:02:08,040 --> 00:02:15,360
Whether you have 1,000 dollars or 10,000 
dollars, stick to this 1% profit rule. 

25
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:20,000
This keeps you safe as your account 
grows, and stops you from getting  

26
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:26,240
overconfident with bigger positions.
 
The truth is most traders struggle because  

27
00:02:26,240 --> 00:02:32,520
they don't treat this like a real business.
They jump in and out of trades randomly,  

28
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:35,720
hoping to get lucky.
But consistent profits  

29
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:40,240
come from having a specific plan.
And you need to stop trading  

30
00:02:40,240 --> 00:02:45,320
once you hit your daily target.
This is important, many traders  

31
00:02:45,320 --> 00:02:51,680
give back their gains by getting greedy.
If you make your 1% goal in one trade,  

32
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:55,840
great! Pack it up and come back tomorrow!
 
Lot Scaling Method 

33
00:02:55,840 --> 00:02:59,440
When you start, you start 
with minimal position size. 

34
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:06,920
But after reaching a 20% account increase, you 
start to increase your lots or contracts slightly. 

35
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:12,000
This progressive scaling matches 
account growth with position size.
  

36
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,320
A small account means being 
smart about position sizing. 

37
00:03:16,320 --> 00:03:21,160
You'll want to begin with the smallest 
possible lot size, typically micro lots  

38
00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:27,200
in forex or minimal shares in stocks.
This approach protects your capital  

39
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:31,000
while you build consistency.
Instead of rushing to trade  

40
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:37,440
bigger positions, you first prove you can 
make steady profits, with minimal risk. 

41
00:03:37,440 --> 00:03:42,160
This keeps you in the game long 
enough to actually grow your account.
  

42
00:03:42,160 --> 00:03:46,400
The beauty of lot scaling lies 
in its natural progression. 

43
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:52,040
You start with micro-positions where 
even a bad trade won't hurt much. 

44
00:03:52,040 --> 00:03:58,360
And once your account grows by 20%, you 
can slightly increase your position size. 

45
00:03:58,360 --> 00:04:03,280
This means your risk stays proportional 
to your account size - you're not suddenly  

46
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:08,680
taking massive positions, just 
because you had a few good trades.
  

47
00:04:08,680 --> 00:04:13,720
Many day traders make the mistake of 
increasing their position size too quickly,  

48
00:04:13,720 --> 00:04:21,440
after a winning streak. This often leads to wiping 
out all previous gains with one or two bad trades. 

49
00:04:21,440 --> 00:04:26,160
You know what I’m talking about! 
We’ve all lost all our previous gains,  

50
00:04:26,160 --> 00:04:30,760
with one, impulsive bad trade!
Smart scaling prevents this  

51
00:04:30,760 --> 00:04:36,360
common pitfall, by keeping your risk 
consistent with your account growth.
  

52
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:40,960
Your trading setup doesn't change 
- only the position size does. 

53
00:04:40,960 --> 00:04:45,400
If you're trading successfully with 
1 mini lot, you'll use the exact  

54
00:04:45,400 --> 00:04:52,920
same strategy when you move to 2 mini lots.
The key to successful lot scaling is patience. 

55
00:04:52,920 --> 00:04:58,840
You might spend several months trading the 
smallest position size before increasing it. 

56
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:05,240
This isn't wasted time - it's building a 
solid foundation for larger future trades.
  

57
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:10,040
Position sizing should match your skill 
level, not just your account size. 

58
00:05:10,040 --> 00:05:15,720
Even if your account grows quickly, stick 
to smaller positions until you've proven  

59
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:20,240
consistent profitability over time.
Remember that scaling up too fast  

60
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:24,320
can be just as dangerous as not scaling at all. 

61
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:28,960
It’s better to use smaller position 
sizes than your account would allow,  

62
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:35,440
preferring the safety and peace of mind, 
that comes with conservative position sizing. 

63
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:41,840
The goal isn't to reach the largest possible 
position size, it's to grow your account steadily,  

64
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:45,440
while keeping risk under control. 
 
The 2:1 Profit Target Rule 

65
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:51,440
This one is obvious, set profit targets 
at least twice your risk, on each trade. 

66
00:05:51,440 --> 00:05:56,480
If risking 50 dollars, aim for 
at least 100 dollars profit. 

67
00:05:56,480 --> 00:06:03,440
This positive risk-reward ratio helps small 
accounts grow, even with a 40% win rate. 

68
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:09,360
So for every dollar you risk, you aim 
to make at least two dollars in profit. 

69
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:15,640
This simple rule shifts the odds in your favor, 
even if you lose more trades than you win.
  

70
00:06:15,640 --> 00:06:22,280
Most traders get this backwards - they grab 
tiny profits, but let their losses grow too big. 

71
00:06:22,280 --> 00:06:26,640
This kills small accounts, fast!
The right way is to flip this  

72
00:06:26,640 --> 00:06:33,360
around – to keep your losses small, and let your 
profits run, until they're double your risk. 

73
00:06:33,360 --> 00:06:38,960
The beauty of this approach shows up when you 
have losing streaks, and everyone has them! 

74
00:06:38,960 --> 00:06:43,720
You can be wrong more often 
than right and still make money! 

75
00:06:43,720 --> 00:06:49,440
This rule keeps your emotions in check too.
You know exactly where you're getting out - win  

76
00:06:49,440 --> 00:06:55,360
or lose, before you even enter the trade. 
 
You see, many traders think they need to win  

77
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:59,680
most of their trades to make money.
But that's not true at all. 

78
00:06:59,680 --> 00:07:05,920
With a 2 to 1 profit target, you can 
lose six trades, and win four out of ten,  

79
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:10,560
and you'll still end up in green.
This takes enormous pressure off  

80
00:07:10,560 --> 00:07:14,160
each individual trade!
Day trading isn't about  

81
00:07:14,160 --> 00:07:20,979
perfection - it's about giving yourself room 
to be wrong, while still making money. 
 
 
  

82
00:07:20,979 --> 00:07:22,200
The Three-Strike Rule
Stop trading after  

83
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:28,080
three consecutive losses in one day.
This preserves capital and prevents emotional  

84
00:07:28,080 --> 00:07:35,160
revenge trading that often follows losing streaks.
Day trading needs clear stopping points,  

85
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:40,200
to protect your money and your mind.
This three-strike rule acts like a  

86
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:45,880
safety net: after three losses in a 
row, you step away from the screen.
  

87
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:50,520
New traders often fall into a 
dangerous trap after losing trades. 

88
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:56,040
They try to win back their money right 
away, trading bigger or taking risky setups  

89
00:07:56,040 --> 00:07:59,440
they normally wouldn't touch.
But three consecutive losses  

90
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:06,400
signal something's of, either with the 
market, your strategy, or your mental state.
  

91
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:10,040
The power of this rule shows 
up in your account balance. 

92
00:08:10,040 --> 00:08:16,880
Instead of turning a bad morning into a terrible 
day, you preserve your capital for tomorrow. 

93
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:22,960
Markets open every day, there's no need to 
force trades when things aren't working. 

94
00:08:22,960 --> 00:08:27,880
Most trading mistakes happen when 
emotions take over after losses. 

95
00:08:27,880 --> 00:08:34,280
This is almost guaranteed: you will start revenge 
trading, you will start taking trades outside  

96
00:08:34,280 --> 00:08:40,800
your plan, just to get back at the market. 
 
Small accounts can't handle big drawdowns,  

97
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:47,080
so you need firm rules about when to stop.
When you have a solid risk management,  

98
00:08:47,080 --> 00:08:53,280
three losses might cost you 1 or 2% 
of your account…but without this rule,  

99
00:08:53,280 --> 00:08:59,880
an emotional spiral could cost much more.
Day trading isn't about being in the market  

100
00:08:59,880 --> 00:09:06,280
all day. Some days the market just won't 
match your strategy, and that's fine! 

101
00:09:06,280 --> 00:09:11,280
The three-strike rule gives you permission 
to step away, and save your money for  

102
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:13,800
better opportunities.
 
The Breakeven Technique 

103
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:20,080
When in profit, at 1 to 1 risk-reward, 
try to move your stop to break even, if  

104
00:09:20,080 --> 00:09:27,840
the price action allows it, and let the trade run.
In day trading, preservation comes before profits. 

105
00:09:27,840 --> 00:09:33,000
And moving your stop loss to breakeven, 
stands as one of the smartest ways to  

106
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:37,080
protect your small account.
This means shifting your stop  

107
00:09:37,080 --> 00:09:42,320
loss to your entry price, once the trade 
moves in your favor, making sure you  

108
00:09:42,320 --> 00:09:49,720
don't turn a winning trade into a losing one.
 
Day trading must start with shifting your mindset  

109
00:09:49,720 --> 00:09:56,040
from chasing profits, to protecting what you have.
Most traders burn their accounts because  

110
00:09:56,040 --> 00:10:03,280
they focus only on potential gains.
But good traders flip this thinking upside down,  

111
00:10:03,280 --> 00:10:10,320
they obsess over protecting their capital first.
Every trade begins with "how much could I lose”,  

112
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:15,440
instead of "how much could I win".
 
Growing a small account starts with  

113
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:20,240
you becoming a “breakeven” trader.
This means learning to protect your  

114
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:28,000
capital, while gaining real market experience.
Think of breakeven like a safety net in trading. 

115
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:32,320
The trade becomes "free" - you can't 
lose money anymore, but you still  

116
00:10:32,320 --> 00:10:36,520
have all the upside potential.
 
Of course, the timing of moving  

117
00:10:36,520 --> 00:10:41,120
to breakeven matters a lot.
Many traders make the mistake  

118
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:46,640
of moving their stop to breakeven too 
quickly, when they see a small profit. 

119
00:10:46,640 --> 00:10:52,280
This often leads to getting stopped out, 
right before the market makes its real move. 

120
00:10:52,280 --> 00:10:57,862
Wait for price to prove itself by 
reaching that 1 to 1 mark first.
  

121
00:10:57,862 --> 00:10:59,400
The Half-Size Rule
Trade half your normal  

122
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:07,080
size when testing new markets or strategies. 
Only increase after 10 successful trades. 

123
00:11:07,080 --> 00:11:14,680
This simple rule helps you avoid costly mistakes 
that come from jumping in too big, too fast. 

124
00:11:14,680 --> 00:11:19,760
The reality is that everyone makes 
mistakes when testing new strategies. 

125
00:11:19,760 --> 00:11:23,960
And we all like to test 
new concepts and new ideas. 

126
00:11:23,960 --> 00:11:29,240
But many traders don’t adjust their positions, 
because they're eager to make money fast. 

127
00:11:29,920 --> 00:11:36,720
After all, a new strategy is still untested, 
you don’t want to enter with full positions. 

128
00:11:36,720 --> 00:11:42,720
Half positions let you gain real market 
experience, while keeping your risk small.
  

129
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:47,360
And don't rush to increase your size 
- wait for at least 10 profitable  

130
00:11:47,360 --> 00:11:54,760
trades before thinking about trading bigger.
Those 10 trades aren't just about making money. 

131
00:11:54,760 --> 00:11:59,240
They show you how that new strategy 
handles different market conditions. 

132
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:04,280
You might face fast markets, 
slow markets, news events,  

133
00:12:04,280 --> 00:12:08,880
or different levels of volatility.
Half positions let you learn from  

134
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:13,640
all these situations, without 
taking big hits to your account. 

135
00:12:13,640 --> 00:12:18,960
And let’s face it, that new strategy 
might come with more losing trades. 

136
00:12:18,960 --> 00:12:24,055
Trading half size means these 
losses won't hurt as much. 
 
 

137
00:12:24,055 --> 00:12:27,200
The Start of Session Rule
Trade only the first 3 hours of the session,  

138
00:12:27,200 --> 00:12:34,520
when volatility and opportunities are highest. 
This prevents overtrading during slow periods. 

139
00:12:34,520 --> 00:12:40,480
Trading the start of the session gives you 
the best mix of volatility and opportunity. 

140
00:12:40,480 --> 00:12:44,520
It doesn’t matter if it’s the 
London session, or the New York one. 

141
00:12:44,520 --> 00:12:49,640
The first three hours of the sessions 
are the sweet spot for active traders. 

142
00:12:49,640 --> 00:12:55,960
The sessions pack more action because big players 
are setting up their positions for the day. 
  

143
00:12:55,960 --> 00:13:01,920
This creates the perfect environment for 
small account traders to catch strong moves. 

144
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:07,000
You see, many new traders make the mistake 
of sitting at their screens all day. 

145
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,920
But here's the thing, it’s better to 
“work” when the market is most active. 

146
00:13:11,920 --> 00:13:18,920
The early session brings more volatility, which 
means faster moves and better profit potential. 
  

147
00:13:18,920 --> 00:13:22,240
After these first three hours, many markets slow  

148
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:28,320
down as institutional traders head to 
lunch, or get caught up in meetings. 

149
00:13:28,320 --> 00:13:33,040
Trading during these slower 
periods may lead to forced trades. 

150
00:13:33,040 --> 00:13:37,960
The morning session gives you the best 
chance to catch meaningful moves.
  

151
00:13:37,960 --> 00:13:43,440
A structured morning routine helps you 
prepare for these important trading hours. 

152
00:13:43,440 --> 00:13:49,160
Before the start of the session, you should 
look for potential price levels and setups. 

153
00:13:49,160 --> 00:13:54,160
This preparation lets you act quickly, 
when real opportunities show up. 

154
00:13:54,160 --> 00:13:59,280
Again, trading only the morning session 
also protects you from the common mistake  

155
00:13:59,280 --> 00:14:01,680
of overtrading.
When you know you  

156
00:14:01,680 --> 00:14:08,334
only trade during specific hours, you will 
become more selective with your setups. 
 
  

157
00:14:08,334 --> 00:14:09,960
The Range Measurement Rule
Calculate the average daily  

158
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:18,240
range and only take trades in the first 70% of 
that range. This prevents late-day choppy trades. 

159
00:14:18,240 --> 00:14:24,000
An underrated part of day trading is being 
on the right part of the daily range. 

160
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:27,760
Markets follow a predictable 
pattern - they usually make  

161
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:33,840
their biggest moves early in the session.
These moves build up to create what we call  

162
00:14:33,840 --> 00:14:39,960
the daily range, which is the difference between 
the highest and lowest prices of the day. 
  

163
00:14:39,960 --> 00:14:47,600
I advise you to focus on the first 70% of this 
range, where the strongest price movement happens. 

164
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:52,600
In the early parts of the daily range, you'll 
find the cleanest moves because that's when  

165
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:58,800
institutional traders are most active.
 
The math behind this is straightforward.  

166
00:14:58,800 --> 00:15:03,440
You look at the previous few 
days' ranges and find the average. 

167
00:15:03,440 --> 00:15:07,880
There are many Tradingview indicators 
that can show the daily range. 

168
00:15:07,880 --> 00:15:13,040
This gives you a good idea of how much 
the market typically moves in a day. 

169
00:15:13,040 --> 00:15:18,440
Once price has moved about 70% of 
that average range, the quality  

170
00:15:18,440 --> 00:15:24,680
of trades often drops significantly.
 
You see, trading small accounts requires  

171
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:29,320
extra care with risk management.
By limiting yourself to the first  

172
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:35,240
70% of the daily range, you're trading 
when the market is most predictable. 

173
00:15:35,240 --> 00:15:40,640
After this point, the market often 
becomes choppy and less directional.
  

174
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:45,480
Many traders make the mistake of 
chasing trades late in the range. 

175
00:15:45,480 --> 00:15:50,880
But here's what happens - after the 
market has made its main move for the day,  

176
00:15:50,880 --> 00:15:56,520
price action becomes more random.
This randomness creates false signals  

177
00:15:56,520 --> 00:16:02,120
that can trap inexperienced traders.
 
The daily range strategy works especially  

178
00:16:02,120 --> 00:16:07,640
well for small accounts, because it keeps 
you focused on high-probability setups. 

179
00:16:07,640 --> 00:16:13,120
Instead of trying to squeeze trades from a 
tired market, you concentrate your efforts  

180
00:16:13,120 --> 00:16:18,080
when price movement is most reliable.
 
Remember that day trading gives you  

181
00:16:18,080 --> 00:16:24,360
lots of opportunities, but these opportunities 
aren't equally distributed throughout the day. 

182
00:16:24,360 --> 00:16:29,000
The best moves happen within that 
first part of the daily range. 

183
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:35,680
This approach also helps prevent overtrading.
Once you've identified the average daily range,  

184
00:16:35,680 --> 00:16:39,960
you know exactly when to be 
active and when to step back. 

185
00:16:39,960 --> 00:16:44,880
This discipline protects your small 
account from unnecessary losses,  

186
00:16:44,880 --> 00:16:50,960
during choppy market conditions.
 
You can see this principle at work in any market. 

187
00:16:50,960 --> 00:16:57,160
Take Amazon stock as an example – you might catch 
a clean move in the morning, when the stock is  

188
00:16:57,160 --> 00:17:02,240
making its primary move for the day.
But trying to trade the same stock,  

189
00:17:02,240 --> 00:17:09,420
after it's moved through most of its daily 
range, often leads to frustration and losses.
  

190
00:17:09,420 --> 00:17:12,360
The Time Stop Method
Exit any trade that hasn't hit profit target  

191
00:17:12,360 --> 00:17:19,280
within that day. This prevents getting stuck 
in non-moving positions or future market gaps. 

192
00:17:19,280 --> 00:17:24,920
“Time stops” rank among the most effective 
tools, especially with a small account. 

193
00:17:24,920 --> 00:17:30,680
The basic idea is simple - if a trade 
isn't working within a set time, you exit. 

194
00:17:30,680 --> 00:17:35,160
This keeps your money from getting 
stuck in trades that go nowhere.
  

195
00:17:35,160 --> 00:17:40,960
You already know this, most of your winning 
trades showed their potential quickly. 

196
00:17:40,960 --> 00:17:46,240
When you enter a trade and it just sits 
there, doing nothing, that's often a sign  

197
00:17:46,240 --> 00:17:51,240
that your timing wasn't quite right. 
 
Professional traders know something  

198
00:17:51,240 --> 00:17:58,160
that beginners often miss: your trading edge 
exists because you spotted a market imbalance. 

199
00:17:58,160 --> 00:18:02,520
That imbalance should create 
price movement pretty quickly. 

200
00:18:02,520 --> 00:18:08,160
When the market just sits there after 
your entry, your trade lacks momentum.
  

201
00:18:08,160 --> 00:18:15,000
Day traders often fall into the trap of waiting 
too long, hoping a trade will eventually work out. 

202
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:19,920
So they wait. They turn a one-day 
trade, into a swing trade. 

203
00:18:19,920 --> 00:18:26,400
The problem is they focus too much on entries, 
and forget about common sense exit strategies. 

204
00:18:26,400 --> 00:18:31,240
With a small account, you can't afford 
to let your money sit idle in trades that  

205
00:18:31,240 --> 00:18:37,360
aren't moving, even if your stop wasn’t hit!
Every minute your money sits in a non-moving  

206
00:18:37,360 --> 00:18:44,080
trade, is costing you potential profits elsewhere.
You need your capital free to take advantage of  

207
00:18:44,080 --> 00:18:49,320
real opportunities, not tied 
up in trades going sideways.
  

208
00:18:49,320 --> 00:18:56,120
There are two smart ways to use time stops. You 
can either exit at market price when the day ends,  

209
00:18:56,120 --> 00:19:02,080
or you can move your stop loss very close 
to the current price, when in profit. 

210
00:19:02,080 --> 00:19:08,920
The second approach gives the trade a tiny bit 
more room, while still protecting your capital.
 
  

211
00:19:08,920 --> 00:19:14,120
Remember that markets move in bursts.
The best trades often work quickly,  

212
00:19:14,120 --> 00:19:19,720
showing momentum and clear direction.
Think of time stops as a way to keep  

213
00:19:19,720 --> 00:19:24,760
your trading focused and efficient.
You're in the market to catch moves,  

214
00:19:24,760 --> 00:19:29,960
not to watch your money sit idle. 
 
And for maximum protection, you should  

215
00:19:29,960 --> 00:19:37,400
close your trades before major economic news.
Small accounts can't handle news volatility! 

216
00:19:37,400 --> 00:19:44,120
Your safest move is to close trades 5 or 10 
minutes before any significant news release. 

217
00:19:44,120 --> 00:19:50,800
For really big events like interest rate 
decisions, you might want to close even earlier. 

218
00:19:50,800 --> 00:19:56,600
This prevents you from getting caught in the 
extreme volatility that news can create.
  

219
00:19:56,600 --> 00:20:00,920
It may be tempting to let your 
trade run during these conditions.  

220
00:20:00,920 --> 00:20:05,240
It might even help your position.
But think about news trading like  

221
00:20:05,240 --> 00:20:11,160
driving in extreme weather - sure, you 
could do it, but why take the extra risk? 

222
00:20:11,160 --> 00:20:16,840
News creates slippage, meaning your stops 
might not fill at the prices you expect. 

223
00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:21,080
Your 20-pip stop loss could 
turn into a 40-pip one! 

224
00:20:21,080 --> 00:20:26,922
This becomes especially dangerous with a 
small account where every dollar counts.
  

225
00:20:26,922 --> 00:20:30,240
The Higher Timeframe Confirmation Rule
Only take trades that align with the daily trend. 

226
00:20:30,240 --> 00:20:34,320
Trading with higher timeframe 
confirmation stands as one of the  

227
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:40,520
smartest approaches for small account growth.
The daily trend acts like a roadmap,  

228
00:20:40,520 --> 00:20:46,520
showing you the safest path for your trades.
 
Patterns that work with the daily trend direction  

229
00:20:46,520 --> 00:20:51,880
have higher win rates, and produce 
cleaner moves. With a small account,  

230
00:20:51,880 --> 00:20:57,800
you can't afford to take many losing trades, 
so this edge becomes extremely valuable. 

231
00:20:57,800 --> 00:21:03,600
Trading in the direction of the daily trend 
puts the big institutional money on your side. 

232
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:09,600
When you spot a setup on a smaller timeframe that 
matches the daily direction, you're essentially  

233
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:16,000
riding the coattails of larger players.
 
A key insight many traders miss is that  

234
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:22,360
countertrend moves tend to be shorter and more 
unpredictable. While you might see impressive  

235
00:21:22,360 --> 00:21:29,800
countertrend runs on smaller timeframes, they 
usually end up feeding back into the main trend. 

236
00:21:29,800 --> 00:21:35,240
This makes fighting the daily trend 
a dangerous game for small accounts.
  

237
00:21:35,240 --> 00:21:39,520
So use multiple timeframes 
to fine-tune your entries. 

238
00:21:39,520 --> 00:21:45,760
You might spot a pattern on a lower chart, 
but checking the 4-hour, or the daily trend,  

239
00:21:45,760 --> 00:21:50,720
helps confirm if it's worth taking.
The best trading opportunities often  

240
00:21:50,720 --> 00:21:55,680
appear when multiple timeframes align.
Think of it like layers of  

241
00:21:55,680 --> 00:22:00,680
confirmation - when your shorter-term 
trading signal matches the daily trend,  

242
00:22:00,680 --> 00:22:06,760
you're stacking probabilities in your favor.
This becomes especially important when trading  

243
00:22:06,760 --> 00:22:10,544
with limited capital.
 
 
Position Sizing Rule 

244
00:22:10,544 --> 00:22:14,680
Position sizing represents the 
cornerstone of risk management in trading. 

245
00:22:14,680 --> 00:22:21,240
Such calculator, like this one on “My FX Book” 
site, will help you protect your capital and  

246
00:22:21,240 --> 00:22:28,040
maintain consistent risk across all trades.
Let’s say you have a 1,000 dollars account,  

247
00:22:28,040 --> 00:22:34,800
risking 1% per trade.
And let’s say your stop loss requires 50 pips. 

248
00:22:34,800 --> 00:22:39,880
The calculator shows you should 
trade 0.02 lots, which means  

249
00:22:39,880 --> 00:22:47,400
you’ll will risk 10 dollars, (1% of the account).
 
This calculator prevents emotional decisions. 

250
00:22:47,400 --> 00:22:52,280
Instead of randomly picking trade 
sizes, it does the math for you. 

251
00:22:52,280 --> 00:23:00,000
With a 1,000 dollars account, risking 10 dollars 
per trade, which is 1%, means you can withstand  

252
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:06,720
many losing trades without damaging your account.
This systematic approach prevents the common  

253
00:23:06,720 --> 00:23:12,720
mistake of randomly choosing position 
sizes, or overleveraging your account. 

254
00:23:12,720 --> 00:23:19,400
This calculator enforces discipline.
 
The beauty of this system is its scalability. 

255
00:23:19,400 --> 00:23:24,600
As your account grows, your position 
sizes will automatically increase,  

256
00:23:24,600 --> 00:23:31,360
while maintaining the same percentage risk.
This allows for steady, controlled account growth,  

257
00:23:31,360 --> 00:23:35,880
without taking excessive risks 
that could damage your capital. 

258
00:23:35,880 --> 00:23:40,920
For small account traders, this 
calculator becomes even more critical. 

259
00:23:40,920 --> 00:23:45,720
A small account has no room for 
error, and one oversized position  

260
00:23:45,720 --> 00:23:52,800
can wipe out months of careful trading.
Using exact position sizes removes emotion  

261
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:56,320
and guesswork from your trading decisions.
 
Mechanical Strategy Development 

262
00:23:56,320 --> 00:24:01,200
To grow a small account, you need 
a mechanical trading strategy. 

263
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:06,680
That’s why you need to focus on creating 
repeatable, systematic processes,  

264
00:24:06,680 --> 00:24:11,920
rather than discretionary trading. 
 
A mechanical strategy means you define  

265
00:24:11,920 --> 00:24:16,520
exact rules for everything.
You spot a specific signal,  

266
00:24:16,520 --> 00:24:21,960
you check specific conditions, and you 
take the trade if everything lines up. 

267
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:28,480
No guessing, no hoping, no emotional 
decisions about "feeling good" about a trade. 

268
00:24:28,480 --> 00:24:33,920
Your strategy needs clear rules for when 
to enter, where to place your stop loss,  

269
00:24:33,920 --> 00:24:38,440
and how to exit with profit.
Without clear rules, you'll  

270
00:24:38,440 --> 00:24:45,080
find yourself making different decisions 
each time, which destroys consistency.
  

271
00:24:45,080 --> 00:24:50,120
The power of mechanical trading 
shines during tough market conditions. 

272
00:24:50,120 --> 00:24:53,920
For your small account, the 
strategy needs to be simple. 

273
00:24:53,920 --> 00:24:58,480
You might start with a basic support 
and resistance, or supply or demand  

274
00:24:58,480 --> 00:25:03,760
strategy, with clear rules.
You buy when price bounces off a key  

275
00:25:03,760 --> 00:25:10,560
level with a specific candlestick pattern, 
sell when price hits resistance. Simple,  

276
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:16,440
but effective when followed consistently.
 
 
The hard truth about mechanical trading  

277
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:19,920
is that it feels boring.
You might watch the market make  

278
00:25:19,920 --> 00:25:25,080
moves without taking trades, because 
your specific conditions aren't met. 

279
00:25:25,080 --> 00:25:32,360
This is good. Trading should feel like operating 
machinery, not like gambling at a casino. 

280
00:25:32,360 --> 00:25:37,360
Many traders resist mechanical trading 
because it removes the excitement. 

281
00:25:37,360 --> 00:25:41,320
They want to feel smart by 
making discretionary decisions. 

282
00:25:41,320 --> 00:25:45,440
But with a small account, 
you can't afford this luxury. 

283
00:25:45,440 --> 00:25:49,040
Every decision must come 
from your pre-planned rules. 

284
00:25:49,040 --> 00:25:55,440
Each trade must follow the exact same process, 
regardless of how you feel about the market.
  

285
00:25:55,440 --> 00:26:01,080
Your mechanical rules protect you from 
the biggest enemy in trading - yourself. 

286
00:26:01,080 --> 00:26:05,960
When real money moves at stake, we 
tend to make emotional decisions. 

287
00:26:05,960 --> 00:26:11,480
A mechanical strategy acts as a shield 
against these emotional impulses. 

288
00:26:11,480 --> 00:26:15,520
So start by writing down 
every rule of your strategy. 

289
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:22,400
Entry conditions, exit conditions, position 
sizing - everything must be specific enough,  

290
00:26:22,400 --> 00:26:27,160
that another person could follow 
your rules and get the same results. 

291
00:26:27,160 --> 00:26:34,160
The goal is to find a simple, repeatable process 
that gives you a small edge, then execute it  

292
00:26:34,160 --> 00:26:39,000
flawlessly through mechanical rules.
Now, if you want to learn other day  

293
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:50,800
trading strategies, go ahead and 
watch one of these videos next.

